<h2>Snow melt and rain causing widespread flooding in Central Europe</h2>
<br><br>
The first half of January brought wintry conditions over parts of Western Europe with low temperatures and unusually high snow cover for this time of year in the low mountain ranges and partially also in the surrounding lowlands in Germany, northern France and Switzerland. In eastern parts of Switzerland, there was one of the heaviest fresh snowfalls since measurements began, locally with record amounts. At low altitudes in the eastern Alpine valleys, the total amount of new snow reached 70 to 100 cm, at low altitudes in the Valais 30 to 40 cm. Mountain locations received 140 to 170 cm in some areas in the east, and 60 to 100 cm in the west. In the last days of the month, however, a trough coming from the Atlantic pushed back the cold air. A small-scale surface low caused a southwesterly flow (Figure 1) and a significant flow of warm air of subtropical origin, resulting in widespread temperatures above 10 &deg;C at ground level in the lowlands. The freezing (zero-degree) level climbed towards the 2000 m at times, causing thaws throughout the Black Forest and also in large areas of the Alpine region.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2021/SoCEvent_202101_figure1.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2021/SoCEvent_202101_figure1.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Weather analysis map of 30 January 06UTC showing the low situated over the Celtic Sea (source: DWD)</em>
<br><br>
The westerly weather conditions also brought widespread precipitation (Figure 2). At high altitudes of the low mountain ranges of southern Central Europe and the Alps, more than 100 mm accumulated in some areas, locally even 150 mm and more. At the same time, snow depths decreased by 20-80 cm within 48 hours. The combination of thaw and heavy rainfall caused several rivers in the southern half of Germany to be flooded, especially the smaller rivers. The threshold values for 2- and 5-year floods were widely exceeded, locally even 10-year floods. In BÃ¼dingen (central Germany), a protective wall collapsed, allowing large masses of water to flow unhindered into the historic city centre. France had received well-above-normal precipitation already in December 2020 due to many very active low-pressure systems and then again during the second half of January. Therefore, the soils were close to saturation over almost the entire country, locally even saturated by the end of January. Since also here some of the precipitation fell as snow down to the lowlands, the snowmelt after the warming contributed much to the situation of high water and flooding in many parts of the country from 28 January onwards, especially in the north and east of the country. Strong westerly to southwesterly winds also brought milder air and extensive rainfalls to the lowlands of Switzerland. In the mountains, considerable amounts of snow fell again, but with rising snow line. Regionally, roads and railroad lines were interrupted due to very high avalanche danger. At low altitudes on the northern side of the Alps, the heavy rain and melting snow led to flooding in some areas.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2021/SoCEvent_202101_figure2.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2021/SoCEvent_202101_figure2.png" width="550px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: 7-day totals and anomalies of precipitation for 24 to 30 January 2021.</em>
<br><br>
Precipitation in Switzerland in January reached 200 to 300 % of the 1981-2010 norm in large parts of the country. Several measurement sites also reported over 300 % of the norm. Rothenbrunnen in Domleschg, Vaduz and Zermatt recorded the largest surplus with about 340% of the norm. In western Switzerland, on the southern side of the Alps and in the Upper Engadine, the January totals were mostly between 120 and 200 %, locally also slightly above 200 % of the norm. In France, with 100 to 200 mm of precipitation and locally even more, the surplus often reached one and a half to two and a half times the normal over the northeastern and eastern parts of France.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for January 2021</h2>
<br><br>
January was generally colder than the 1981-2010 average in western Europe and warmer in eastern Europe. The number of frost days (days with a minimum temperature below 0 &deg;C, Figure 5) was higher than normal in most parts of western Europe and much below normal in especially southeastern Europe. The number of ice days (days with a maximum temperature below 0 &deg;C, Figure 4) was much higher than normal only in Scandinavia and the Alpine region.
Remarkable high was the number of cold nights in Spain in the beginning of January (Figure 5) and on the contrary the high number of warm night (Figure 6) which occurred mainly at the end of the month. Also Italy, (south)eastern Europe and Iceland counted much more warm nights than on average.
